es 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the common Late Latin name <i>Julianus</i>, a derivative of   Julius .  In classical times <i>Julianus</i> was a name borne not only by various minor early saints, but also by the Roman emperor Julian ‘the Apostate’, who attempted to return the Roman Empire from institutionalized Christianity to paganism. For many centuries the English name <i>Julian</i> was borne by women as well as men, for example by the Blessed Julian of Norwich (  <i>c.</i>1342– after 1413 ). The differentiation in form between <i>Julian</i> and   Gillian   did not develop until the 16th century. <i>Julian</i> is still occasionally used as a girl's name. Notable bearers include the British classical guitarist  Julian Bream  (  b. 1933 ) and the British jazz pianist and bandleader  Julian Joseph  (  b. 1966 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Julyan","meanings":["Modern respelling of   Julian ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":28,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Julian Rockley was born in 1354, in England, her father, Sir John Rockley, was 34 and her mother, Johanna Gerstone, was 29. She married Robert Holme of Paull Holme in 1375, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1411, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 57, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1354–1411":"1354–1411","1344–1380":"1344–1380","1380–1408":"1380–1408","–1418":"–1418","1320–1406":"1320–1406","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1325":"1325","1411":"1411","1344":"1344","1354":"1354","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","1351":"1351","1382":"1382","